> Punchy and smoky with a spicy kick, Cajun spice mix gives any dish a tasty boost. Made with herbs and spices common in Cajun cuisine, this spice mix contains ingredients such as chilli powder, ground cumin, oregano and thyme, making it the perfect match for meat and seafood dishes as well as pasta sauces and stews.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

When boiling, add the @Rigatoni Pasta{180%grams} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Drain the @King Prawns{150%grams}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the garlic and @Cajun Spice Mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Once fragrant, stir through the @Creme Fraiche{150%grams}, @Vegetable Stock Paste{10%grams}, @Sugar{1%tsp} and @Water for the Sauce{100%milliliter}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}.

Bring the sauce to a boil, then lower to a simmer until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the prawns and cook for another ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, stir through the @Peas{120%grams}, cooked pasta and @Butter{20%grams} until the butter has melted, ~{1%minute} more.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

Share your Cajun prawn pasta between your bowls. Enjoy!